The Stoioe held that their prin- ciple of Necessity was involved in the Disjunctive judgment applied to future events, as may be seen argued at length in Fac. 20 folL, e. g. Since it is absolutely necessary that a man now living must at a given date in the future be either dead ‚or alive, whichever of the two proves eventually to be true must be now a necessary truth though unknown to us ; or, more shortly, his existence or non-existence at that date is a necessary truth3 which of the two it is, will be made apparent by the event.
